@node not9 "CRYSTAL SOFTWARE INTERNATIONAL ANNOUNCES NEW AMIGA MAGAZINE"

@{FG Shine}@{B}CRYSTAL SOFTWARE INTERNATIONAL@{UB} ANNOUNCES NEW @{B}AMIGA@{UB} MAGAZINE@{FG Text}
¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/06/15@{FG Text}

Hello Friends!

Allow  me  to  introduce  myself. My name is @{I}Robert Iveson, @{UI}and I'm the Managing
Director  of  the @{B}Amiga@{UB} Publishing Department of @{B}Crystal Software International@{UB}.
I'm also the editor & writer of a brand new, forthcoming magazine entitled @{B}Amiga
Survivor@{UB}.

This  new  'zine  is,  of course, 100% dedicated to the future of the @{B}Amiga@{UB}, and
will include nothing but coverage of @{B}Amiga@{UB} games.

Published  by  the  world-wide  company, @{B}Crystal Software International@{UB} (who has
offices  based  in  the Netherlands, the U.S, the U.K, Australia and Japan) this
new  publication  will be distributed on a worldwide scale, informing @{B}Amiga@{UB} fans
of the planet what's happening on the @{B}Amiga@{UB} games scene.

Like  yourself,  who  are  devoted  to the future of the @{B}Amiga@{UB}, I thought it was
about time a dedicated @{B}Amiga@{UB} games magazine was produced. It's good to know that
after a troublesome three years, the @{B}Amiga@{UB} is finally remaking a name for itself
in the computer-user community. And it's even better to know that many producers
of  new  games,  both  small groups of @{B}Amiga@{UB} fans, as well as larger development
companies  are  creating  more  and  more landmark games that are equal to those
produced  on  today's  top  @{B}PC@{UB}s and consoles. So @{B}Amiga Survivor@{UB} is here to bring
news,  previews  and  reviews  of  all  the  forthcoming  commercial,  freeware,
shareware and licenceware titles.

@{B}Amiga  Survivor@{UB}  has  emerged  from  a  popular small-press fanzine entitled @{B}The
Domain@{UB}  -  the only @{B}Amiga@{UB} PD and Shareware Magazine. After a year of good sales,
@{B}Crystal  Software@{UB}  snapped  up the rights to distribute it worldwide, and due to
its   popular   welcome,  we  have  decided  to  make  the  magazine  much  more
commercialised  and  incorporate  commercial  reviews  and previews, hence @{B}Amiga
Survivor@{UB}.

The  first  issue is set to be released at the end of June / early July, it will
include  regular  articles  such  as @{I}Website of the Month @{UI}, @{I}The Fifth Column @{UI}( a
general  rant  about  the  world  of  computers ), @{I}The Trashcan @{UI}( Software to be
avoided! ), @{I}@{B}Aminet @{UB} Ramble @{UI} (a  monthly  dig  into  the recent @{B}Aminet@{UB} postings),
@{I}Magnetic Fiction @{UI} ( A collection of short stories from @{I}Andy Campbell @{UI}), @{I}Joe and 
Ami @{UI} ( An  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  related exclusive comic strip ), there'll be a letters page, a
hints  and tips page and a page for readers to submit their own ideas for games.
And,  to  sound like a stereotypical advert... lots LOTS more! But of course the
main  part  of the mag will feature news, previews and reviews of all the latest
games - whether they're commercial or free/shareware.

Already  supported by many of the @{B}Amiga@{UB}'s games developers, (including @{B}ClickBoom@{UB}
who  have supplied review titles of @{B}Quake@{UB} and @{B}Myst@{UB}, @{B}Vulcan Software Ltd@{UB} who have
provided  a review copy of @{B}Genetic Species@{UB} for the first issue, @{B}APC&TCP@{UB}, @{B}Islona@{UB},
@{B}The  Real  Ologram@{UB}...  to  name  but a few) not to mention already have a decent
subscriber  base  from  readers  of  @{B}The domain@{UB}, @{B}Amiga Survivor@{UB} is set to play a
major part in the @{B}Amiga@{UB} games scene.

In  case  you  are  not  familiar with @{B}Crystal Software International@{UB}, then I'll
introduce them to you. They are a multi-platform supporting company, who have an
in-house  group  of  programmers  working on many utilities and games as well as
educational titles. They have recently developed a part of their company for the
production of new @{B}Amiga@{UB} titles, both low and high spec. Some titles currently in
development  are  @{B}Gilbert  Goodmate  &  the Mushroom of Phungoria@{UB}, @{B}Goblin Tanks@{UB},
@{B}Arcangel@{UB}  and @{B}Space Patrol@{UB}. They also have a publication division who distribute
many  magazines  for  many different platforms (such as @{B}Atari@{UB}, @{B}PC@{UB}, @{B}Playstation@{UB} &
@{B}M-Crystal@{UB})

@{B}Crystal  Software@{UB}  also  have  the power to sign up titles from small developing
groups,  their  most  recent being from @{I}Suomi-Peli, @{UI}with their game @{B}Damage - The
Sadistic  Butchery  of Humanity@{UB} (@{B}www.sci.fi/~damage@{UB}) So if you have a small game
in development that requires a publisher - then contact us! (Details below!)

The first issue of @{B}Amiga Survivor@{UB} is set for release at the end of June, and can
be purchased direct from me, the editor, @{I}Robert Iveson @{UI}at the below address.

UK Residents can send a cheque or postal order made payable to @{I}Robert Iveson @{UI}for
2.95,  which  includes  postage  and packing. Overseas customers would be better
contacting  @{B}EPIC MARKETING@{UB} ( @{I}epicmarketing@dialin.net @{UI}) to place their order via
credit card.

Each  issue  will be in A5 format, complete with a colour cover. The first issue
will  have an exclusive review of @{B}Vulcan@{UB}'s @{B}Genetic Species@{UB}, plus a report of the
recent  @{B}World  of  Amiga@{UB}  Show held in London, as well as a review of 'the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
Anthem', not to mention pages of News, Previews and Reviews, and a whole host of
Amiga related articles!

