@node not28 "STATEMENT OF CLOANTO ABOUT SOME COMMON QUESTIONS"

@{FG Shine}STATEMENT OF @{B}CLOANTO@{UB} ABOUT SOME COMMON QUESTIONS@{FG Text}
¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/07/06@{FG Text}

From  time  to  time  we  become aware, through direct user emails and newsgroup
posts,  of  some questions related to our @{B}Amiga@{UB} products and projects. We always
answer  directly  to  all  inquiries,  but we would also like to publicly try to
answer and clarify some of the more popular issues.

No  doubt,  a frequent question is about our plans with respect to @{B}PowerPC Amiga@{UB}
expansion  boards. Last year, when we released a @{B}PowerPC@{UB} version of the @{B}Personal
Paint@{UB} blitting library, we were very proud to be among the first to release some
@{B}PowerPC@{UB}  code  for the @{B}Amiga@{UB}. Since then, we did not port entire packages to the
@{B}PowerPC@{UB}.  This  is  because  porting  a complex program like @{B}Personal Paint@{UB}, for
example,  is not just a matter of simply "recompiling" it, or at least it is not
with  the development tools and the @{B}PowerPC@{UB} libraries available so far. We still
plan  to  do  this  for  @{B}Personal  Paint  8@{UB},  which  is  designed with more code
portability in mind, if the @{B}PowerPC@{UB} will be accepted and endorsed as an official
@{B}Amiga@{UB}  platform, or if tools emerge that make it possible to port @{B}Personal Paint@{UB}
to  a  @{B}PowerPC@{UB}  system  by  using  the same code as for the @{B}68K@{UB} version. In this
latter case, we might even port @{B}Personal Paint 7.x@{UB}.

Another  issue  is  that  the  original  @{B}Personal Paint PowerPC@{UB} blitting library
released  last  year  does  not  work with newer @{B}PowerPC@{UB} expansion systems. This
blitting  library  was  tested  both  by @{B}Cloanto@{UB} and by the manufacturers of the
boards  (who were aware of our release plans), and originally worked flawlessly.
After  the  release of the library on the @{B}Personal Paint 7.1@{UB} CD-ROM, the @{B}PowerPC@{UB}
expansion  systems  were  changed  in  a way that created incompatibilities with
existing  @{B}PowerPC@{UB} software, such as this library. We changed the code twice, and
released it on @{B}Aminet@{UB}, in the @{B}biz/cloan@{UB} directory, and we also shared our source
code  with  the developers of the expansion systems, but given the continued and
repeated  incompatibilities,  we now feel that the maintenance overhead does not
justify  the  performance  improvement, and, as explained, we are looking at the
whole  matter  from  a  broader  perspective. To completely solve this issue, we
recommend  to use the standard @{B}68K@{UB} blitting libraries, which are used by default
by  the  program.  In  our  tests with @{B}Amiga@{UB} systems having both a @{B}PowerPC@{UB} and a
@{B}68060@{UB}  CPU,  the  @{B}68060@{UB}  blitting  library  was only 10% slower than the @{B}PowerPC@{UB}
library.  It  is  to be expected that @{B}PowerPC Amiga@{UB} systems will only be able to
express their full potential when the complete @{B}Amiga OS@{UB} and all new software are
entirely  compiled  for  the  @{B}PowerPC@{UB}.  Before this occurs, and unless it can be
verified  tha at least some software which can justify the overall investment is
available  for  the  @{B}PowerPC@{UB}  and  runs  considerably  faster  than on a real or
emulated  @{B}68K Amiga@{UB}, we recommend to use @{B}68K Amiga@{UB} systems such as the @{B}68060@{UB}, or
emulation.

It  is  no  secret  that,  while the power of the CPUs used in @{B}PC@{UB}s doubles about
every  18  months, we became aware of the fact that an @{B}Amiga@{UB} can now be emulated
quite well by other systems. In some cases, which can only increase rapidly over
time,  emulated  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  systems  are  already cheaper and/or faster than silicon
ones.  Whatever  the  official  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  of the future will be, whether it will be
based  on  a @{B}PowerPC@{UB}, or on a different (non-@{B}68K@{UB}) CPU, it will need emulation to
run  the  current  @{B}Amiga  OS@{UB}  and  applications  (which have now officially been
defined  as "@{B}Classic Amiga@{UB}"). We plan to continue supporting @{B}Amiga@{UB} emulation and
other  means  of  integrating  the @{B}Classic Amiga@{UB} with different platforms, as we
have  successfully done with the @{B}Amiga Forever@{UB} package. We will also continue to
invest  in  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB},  preferably  by focussing on development on one official
platform,  rather  than  politics related to the use of one CPU or the other. In
any case, we plan to release new @{B}Amiga@{UB} products before next Christmas.

These  are  hard  times for commercial @{B}Amiga@{UB} software developers: sales are low,
and  the uncertainty about the future has never been as high as it is now, since
we don't even know what the new @{B}Amiga OS@{UB} we have to write software for will look
like.  We hope that we had a chance to clarify some doubts about our own future,
and we thank all users for their patience and continued support. It appears that
it is now our turn to be patient and wait to see what the future will bring.

For  additional  information  related  to  these  topics,  please  refer  to the
following recently-updated documents:

@{I}@{B}Personal Paint @{UB}Frequently Asked Questions @{UI}
@{B}http://www.cloanto.com/amiga/faq.html@{UB}

@{I}@{B}Amiga @{UB}Emulation: Good or Bad for the @{B}Amiga @{UB}? @{UI}
@{B}http://www.cloanto.com/amiga/forever/emulation_good_bad.html@{UB}
